
Templates are hard-coded using the template instantiation mechanisms contained
in templates/Makefile.temps.  Creating a new template class is a bit tricky.
The target 'base_templates' syntactically processes template header and source
files to create *.Ct and *.Ht files that can be used to instantiate templates.
These files are assumed to be massaged to make the template type names more
distintinguishable, as well as to include some ifdefs that are needed to
instantiate a template.  The basic routine used here is 'gentemp', which has the
syntax:

    gentemp <sourcefile> <headerfile> <class1> ... <classn> -types <type1> ... <typen>

where the class list are the template instantiations, which are assumed to
use the same type names throughout the file.
 
Constructing a template instances is substantially easier (though not quite
easy).  The basic routine is 'instemp':

    instemp <sourcefile> <headerfile> <type1> ... <typen> 
		-headers <header1> ... <headern>
		-classes <class1> ... <classn>

The types are the actual types that match the type list used for gentemp.  The
headers are the files that are included to define the types used during the
instantiation (possibly even other template types).  The class list is the
template_instantiated classnames.  This is generated manually to allow
pointers to be turned into appropriate class names.  Again, the order of these
class names must match the order of the classes listed for gentemp.


The file templates/Makefile.temps defines the base_templates and 
template_instances targets.  It also defines template_objs and 
TEMP_LIBS, which do not need to be updated if a new template instantion is 
created.
